TI  - Tempo-spatial change of landscape pattern in semi-arid agro-pastoral transition area in recent 20 years - a case study in Ejin Holo Banner, Inner Mongolia.
T2  - Journal of Beijing Forestry University
M3  - Journal article
AB  - This study was conducted to investigate the temporal and spatial changes in the semiarid agropastoral landscape in Ejin Holo Banner, Nei Mongol, China. Results show that the whole landscape is changing from a simple and man-made landscape to a diversified and near-natural one, in which change in the early period (1977-87) occurred in the hilly-floodplain mosaic area and in the later period (1098-98) in the whole landscape. Changes in land use structure demonstrated that changes in woodlands focused on area in the early period and on spatial distribution in the later period. Overcutting of shrubs in the early period and the large-scale plantation of shrubs in the later period gave a good explanation of the change in the whole landscape, which proves that shrub plantations will be the optimum measure for the restoration and reconstruction of damaged semiarid landscapes. At the same time, the area and spatial distribution of mobile sandlands were both decreasing; however, the convergence of mobile sandlands may increase the difficulty of sand control. On the other hand, the intactness of these mobile sandlands may be helpful to increase the stability of the whole landscape and to optimize the utility of limited resources in the semiarid area.
