AU  - Lenjiso, Birhanu Megersa
TI  - The gender dimensions of fodder technology adoption in East Africa: Evidence from Ethiopia and Kenya.
T2  - The gender dimensions of fodder technology adoption in East Africa: Evidence from Ethiopia and Kenya
M3  - Book
AB  - This study was conducted in six peasant associations (PA) in Ethiopia and six villages in Kenya to explore the gender dimensions of smallholder fodder technology adoption. The study assessed men's and women's livestock ownership structures and their role in livestock feeding, their fodder trait preferences and role in adoption decisions, their access to information and fodder seed dissemination pathways and the effect of fodder adoption on intra-household resource allocations. It was shown that the livestock ownership structure was similar across the two countries in that men own large livestock, while women own small livestock. However, there was no specific norm that restricts women's livestock ownership in Ethiopia, as was the case in certain parts of Kenya. There were two main categories of fodder trait preferences: productivity-oriented and role-oriented trait preferences. While productivity-oriented trait preferences were shared across genders and determine currently grown fodder, role-oriented trait preferences were mostly expressed by women and less considered in adoption decisions. The final fodder adoption decision was a man's domain in both countries, but women made multiple decisions related to adoption without the knowledge of men, especially in Kenya. Lack of access to innovation information and fodder seed was the major adoption problem in both countries and across genders. In Kenya, the formal information and seed pathways were ineffective and biased against women. In Ethiopia, nongovernmental organizations (NGOs) and development agencies were the major source of information for both men and women. Fodder adoption reduced men's workload and increased milk income at the household level. For women, it not only increased workload but also shifted milk income control to men. In general, both men and women participants emphasized the positive effect of fodder technology adoption on milk production and household income. In conclusion, improving men's and women's access to information, seed pathways, providing drought- and disease-resistant fodder varieties, addressing role-oriented trait preferences, introducing complementary technologies that reduce women's workload and ensuring their control over benefits should increase fodder adoption, improve livestock productivity and thus food security in the region.
PU  - International Livestock Research Institute (ILRI)
