AU  - Ha, Tran Thi Thu
AU  - Dien, Pham Van
ED  - Cairns, Malcolm
ED  - Hill, Bob
ED  - Kurupunya, Tossaporn
TI  - Farming medicinal plants under a forest canopy: innovations by shifting cultivators in the uplands of North Vietnam.
T2  - Farmer innovations and best practices by shifting cultivators in Asia-Pacific
M3  - Book chapter
AB  - The implementation of Doi Moi reforms in Vietnam since the mid-1980s has reshaped land use patterns, particularly impacting shifting cultivation practices among ethnic minority groups. With common land no longer available, shifting cultivators have faced the challenge of adapting to new cultivation systems while balancing government regulations, income generation and livelihood improvement. Despite the historical significance of swidden farming, shrinking forest cover and population pressure led to policy changes aimed at minimizing shifting cultivation and promoting sedentary cultivation for sustainable development. However, after more than 3 decades, these objectives remain largely unmet, with negative impacts such as flooding, landslides and drought threatening upland livelihoods. This chapter explores how upland medicinal plant cultivators under forest canopies have responded to these challenges, striving to secure income while maintaining sustainable micro-environments and livelihood security through innovative land management practices.
