TY  - BOOK
AU  - Yadav, J. S. P.
AU  - Singh, R. K.
AU  - Gupta, V. P.
ED  - Yadav, J. S. P.
ED  - Singh, R. K.
ED  - Gupta, V. P.
TI  - Converting deserts into oasis.
T2  - Converting deserts into oasis
M3  - Book
M3  - Conference proceedings
AB  - Desertification, a historic phenomenon, is degradation of land especially in the arid, semi-arid and dry sub-humid areas, mainly due to deforestation, overgrazing, over withdrawal of groundwater, increased soil salinity, exploitative agriculture, and global climate change. The primary causes are all related to man's overexploitation of the resources and environment, while drought is only a contributing factor to desertification. Desertification occurs in a non-linear and unmappable patterns. An area undergoing desertification is brought to the public attention only after the process is well under way. The world's deserts were formed by natural processes interacting over long intervals of time. According to the United National Convention to Combat Desertification (UNCCD), about 70 per cent of 52 billion hectares of agricultural land in arid areas worldwide are degraded and threatened by desertification. More than 110 countries are affected by desertification. The UNCCD has declared 17th June as the World Day to combat desertification. An India-Afghanistan symposium on converting deserts into oasis was held in New Delhi, India, during November 19-21, 2006, to consider the problems relating to deserts and desertification in the Asia-Pacific region. The symposium was to provide a road map for improving the productivity and sustainability of desert farming systems, specifically in respect of India and Afghanistan. The present book Converting Deserts into Oasis contains 22 chapters based on the key contributions on desertification to the sympsium. Chapter 1 outlines the main objectives of the symposium with emphasis on afforestation, modern techniques and good weather code for sustainable conservation farming in deserts. Chapter 2 deals with the major ongoing activities under World Food programme in India and Afghanistan. Chapters 3 and Chapter 5 discussed extensively the various farm technologies validated at international level, especially with respect to integrated watershed management. Chapter 4 is related to disasters management and risk insurance model. Chapters 6 and 18 give the overall view of agriculture with future needs including livelihood security by enhancing potato productivity in Afghanistan. Chapter 7 deals with the problems of sustainable development through technological interventions including the role of women in Thar Desert of Rajasthan. Chapter 8 highlights the various technologies concerning livestock and crop improvement as well as harnessing wind and solar energy in the cold desert of Western Himalayas. Chapters 9 and 10 provide information on various available agro-met services and weather-based pests forecasting for managing Indian and Afghanistan deserts. Chapter 11 outlines the scope of different techniques available in respect of remote sensing and information technology for drought assessment. Chapter 12 deals with advancement in indigenous methods of water harvesting and its use efficiency as well as control of wind erosion in Arid Rajasthan. Chapter 13 deals with methods of managing poor quality waters for mitigating drought, whereas Chapter 14 is devoted to gene mining for developing drought resistant crop varieties. Chapter 15 describes the management strategies for resource mobilization and outsourcing. Chapter 16 focuses on the utility of shelterbelts in the arid zones and Chapter 17 details various agro-forestry technologies for preventing deserts. Chapters 19, 20, 21 and 22 provide exhaustive account of livestock management through grassland development, nutrition, health improvement and other related interventions in arid regions.
