AU  - Nho, Nguyn Thanh
TI  - Potential mangrove environmental buyers and services in Hai Phong, Vietnam.
T2  - CIFOR Occasional Paper
M3  - Bulletin
AB  - It is becoming increasingly urgent to assess the potential payment for environmental services provided by mangroves, as it will help to increase the total PFES revenue and stakeholders' awareness of the immense value that the mangroves provide. Mangroves bring economic sectors, thereby protecting mangroves more effectively. However, building a payment mechanism for forest environmental services is currently facing many difficulties due to the lack of information related to "Pay for which service? Who is paying? How much is the payment? How's the payment?" Answering these four questions requires a lot of well-conducted research over a sufficiently long period of time. This report aims to answer the first two questions based on the case study in Hai Phong. The report shows that the Payment Mechanism for Forest Environmental Services (PFES) for mangroves in Vietnam can be applied to eight main types of environmental services: (1) Absorption, storage, and storage services; (2) Services to reduce sedimentation and sludge volume; (3) Coastal erosion control services; (4) Breakwater service; (5) Service of providing clean water, filtering heavy metals and pollutants; (6) The service of providing spawning grounds; (7) Landscape beauty services; and (8) Food ingredient supply services. The research results also show that there are 20 potential groups of buyers of mangrove environmental services in Hai Phong, including: dredging companies, energy companies, entertainment industry, banking industry, industry. air transport, fishing port, seaport, coastal economic zone, sand mining company, mining and metallurgy industry, transportation industry, thermal power industry, dyke management groups, tourism companies tourism, residential communities, shipbuilding industry, companies producing agricultural, forestry, fishery products, petroleum companies and clean water companies. While some buyer groups have shown a high level of commitment to making payments, more future research is needed to understand the willingness of the remaining parties to participate in PFES.
