AU  - Schultz, B.
TI  - Implications of water management on food security and environment in Tigray, Ethiopia.
T2  - Transactions of the 19th International Congress on Irrigation and Drainage, Beijing, China, 2005. Vol 1A: Improving  water and land management for increasing efficiency in irrigated agriculture 
M3  - Conference paper
AB  - A study of two of earthen dam irrigation development schemes, Gumsalasa and Korir, in Ethiopia's drought-affected Tigray Province, has revealed that irrigation is playing a very important role in improving the livelihood of the region's poor farmers. An increase in yield of 170 - 285% has been recorded. Since the introduction of irrigation, the cropping pattern has changed from small grains to maize and vegetables. The yield, the market prices and subsequently the household income generated from the irrigated fields are higher than in the rainfed situation. However, individual farmers are still able to decide the length of their delivery times, and wastage of irrigation water by runoff and over-watering is a common practice. This has negative implications for food security and the environment. For instance, the areas irrigated at the 2 schemes are 55% and 60% respectively of what was originally planned. The resulting increases in soil salinity are not yet harmful to crop production, but its extent has increased by more than 200% over a four year period.
