AU  - Subhash Dubey, Subhash Dubey
TI  - Deviation on seed germination, growth and biomass performance ofJatropha curcasL. as predisposed by plantation period and water intensity.
T2  - Journal of Interacademicia
M3  - Journal article
AB  - An experiment was conducted at Research and Development farm, Ruchi Biofuel Private Limited Maheshwer (situated between 24°22°12′25N latitude, 75°35′26E longitudes, at an elevation of 600 m above the mean sea level) to determine the variation on seed germination, growth and biomass performance ofJatropha curcasL. as influenced by plantation period and water intensity. In central parts of India, larger areas are under semiarid and arid conditions with a moderate-to-high risk of drought. The drought resistant plant,Jatropha curcasL., familyEuphorbiaceae, can grow on lands not suited for agriculture, improve the environment and supply raw material for local communities is attractive for resource-poor farmers. Although Jatropha is commonly planted in India, research on cultivation and propagation of Jatropha is limited. This study provides documentation of the germination of Jatropha seeds planted in nursery as influenced by plantation period and water intensity. The study shows high viability of the seeds with a mean germination rate above 40% and germination completed within 8 days. Shorter germination takes place (4.7 days) as water intensity of 2 days/week during the month of May as compared to other water intensity level as 3 and 4 times/week. Temperature and water intensity level is significantly (P=0.01). effecting the days of germination as temperature was maximum (45.3°C) during the month of May shortest germination period was occurred as increasing of water intensity from 3 to 4 time the moisture level of soil become increase and caused decrease in soil temperature and longer germination period takes place. Whereas days of germination was found longer during the month of March (10.5 days) with the water intensity level of 4 times/week. Germinations trials made in February had a faster germination rate of 1.4-1.6 days compared to the other trials. Seeds dropped during the month of May revealed maximum germination percentage (47.54%) and minimum germination was exhibited during the month of February (40.34%). The germination and related parameters exhibited that seed sown during the month of April was the best period for seed germination and growth parameters forJatropha curcas. Geographical factors exhibited negative correlation (P=0.05) with germination, shoot length and biomass. Latitudinal ingredient are influencing seed germination and biomass as its exhibiting highly positive correlation (P=0.01). While longitude is not controlling water intensity on seed germination, collar diameter and shoot biomass, as it's appears to have a negative impact on the germination and growth as well. This incidence that the differences observed of sowing session may very well be influenced by seasonal variation of respective sources spread over an immense geographical area, experiencing varied environmental conditions. However, the results indicate that showing period has a positive impact on the growth rate after germination. Likewise, the intensity of watering and temperature seems to have a fundamental impact on the germination rate and growth pattern.
