AU  - Khin Sandar Linn, Khin Sandar Linn
AU  - Cho Cho San, Cho Cho San
TI  - Gender perspective on technology adoption of rice production in Thazi Township, Myanmar.
T2  - Journal of Agricultural Research
M3  - Journal article
AB  - The study attempted to observe adoption of the sample rice growers on rice technology package recommended by Department of Agriculture (DoA) in Thazi Township, to identify the role of agricultural trainings with gender perspective in adoption, to find out the constraints for rice growers regarding the improved rice production technology adoption and to examine factors influencing the gender's role in adoption of improved rice production technologies. Total rice producers 121 male-headed households (HHs) and 66 female-headed households from 11 villages were chosen with purposive random sampling method and descriptive statistics were employed. In adoption study, 16.7% of male-headed households and 9.1% of female-headed households in which 6 to 10 components were adopted involved in high-adopters group. Partial-adopters adopted at least 1 to 5 components of technology recommendation. Recommending ten components of improved technology package adoption of seed rate, seedling age, time of checking and refilling, basal insecticide application and weed control were still weak in both household groups. High-adopters more participated in agricultural trainings. Male-headed households in both adopter groups were comparatively more involved in various trainings. Serious constraints in rice production were water scarcity, labor scarcity, high price of seed and fertilizer and unavailability of quality seeds for both adopters groups. According to the multiple regression results, total cultivated area was negatively correlated with adoption whereas family labor number and total gross benefit were significantly influenced on adoption of both types of households.
