TY  - JOUR
AU  - Mayee, C. D.
TI  - Bt cotton in India: current status and impact on textile industry.
T2  - Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences India. Section B, Biological Sciences
M3  - Journal article
AB  - Cotton is the most important commercial crop in India. It is cultivated on 9.5 m ha by more than 4.0 m small and marginal farmers. Indian textile industry is predominantly cotton-based. In recent years the cotton economy has been accelerating at a much faster pace on all criteria viz., production, consumption, yield and export. This turn around story is basically related to dramatic increase in yield (productivity) and production. Amongst a few factors that are considered to have been responsible for the spectacular change in India, 'Bt-cotton' is currently being regarded to have the most significant impact. Bt cotton was developed by incorporating a delta-endotoxin producing cry1Ac(crystal 1Ac) gene derived from a soil bacterium Bacillus thuringiensis(Berliner) (Bt) into the cotton genome through genetic engineering. The endotoxin is toxic to a wide range of lepidopteran insects including the most damage causing bollworms of cotton. The GM (genetically modified) Bt cotton expresses endotoxin in all plant parts and has successfully managed bollworms thus far. The Government of India permitted the commercial use of Bt cotton for farmers in April, 2002 after a series of biosafety, environmental safety and bio-efficacy trials for four years. Until 2002, for well over a decade, the average production of Indian cotton was stagnant at 15-17 m bales (bale=170 kg lint) with productivity of less than 300 kg lint per ha thereby forcing the textile industry to import cotton so as to enable them to meet the local demand. The constant low yields were primarily due to the immense economic damage caused by the bollworms and the inability of farmers to control them on account of insecticide resistance in the pests. The introduction of Bt cotton was considered as the most appropriate technology under the circumstances. The technology acceptability was so high that the Bt cotton acreage increased from 0.03 m ha in 2002 to 6.3 m ha (that accounts for 66% of total area) by 2007. Bt cotton not only efficiently controlled the bollworms, but also concomitantly reduced the pesticide use by 50% and enhanced the productivity from 300 kg lint per ha in 2001 to 554 kg lint per ha in 2007. The crop output has surpassed all expectations and targeted projection thus contributing to an increase in the export of raw cotton from 0.1 m to 6.5 m bales within last six years. Imports were restricted to 0.5 m bales principally of extra long staple cottons. Bt cotton cultivation has also improved the quality as reported by ITMF survey 2005. The enhanced production has made the textile industry again vibrant which plays a significant role by contribution of 4% of GDP and 20% to the Indian exports. It is the largest employer (after agriculture) of workers directly and indirectly. Availability of raw material has made the textile industry completely self reliant in the entire value-chain from cotton crop to Hi-fashion garment making. Although criticism of the technology continues, farmers who are the primary beneficiaries of Bt cotton have accepted the technology. To sustain it longer, scientists have to address the emerging problems and concerns that are invariably associated with the introduction of modern technologies. The benefits of growing Bt cotton have raised hopes of commercialization of biotechnology for not only other traits like drought, disease, herbicide resistance, fibre quality in cotton but also in other crops in India.
