TY  - JOUR
AU  - Lebel, L.
AU  - Khrutmuang, S.
AU  - Manuta, J.
TI  - Tales from the margins: small fishers in post-tsunami Thailand.
T2  - Disaster Prevention & Management
M3  - Journal article
AB  - Based on direct observations and interviews in fishing communities, this study critically examines how the post-tsunami recovery process has affected the livelihoods of small fisher communities in southern Thailand. It is revealed that the December 2004 Indian Ocean tsunami had immediate devastating and longer-term debilitating consequences for small fisher communities in southern Thailand. Delays in repairing or replacing boats have had a major impact on well-being. By removing housing and other coastal infrastructure, the tsunami also created opportunities for both social and ecological reorganization. These opportunities were seized by powerful interest groups with already strong connections to the state through membership in task forces and other links to power, in particular the tourism and conservation sectors, to the detriment of the interests of small fishers. It is argued that a narrow focus on tourism-led recovery is unlikely to do anything but recover tourism.
