AU  - Smith, C. W.
AU  - Kassier, H. W.
AU  - Cunningham, L.
TI  - The effect of stand density and climatic conditions on the growth and yield ofEucalyptus grandis.
T2  - ICFR Bulletin Series
M3  - Bulletin
AB  - In 1986 a project was initiated to evaluate the effects of initial stand density on the growth and yield of short rotation fast growingEucalyptusspecies suited to the summer rainfall conditions of South Africa. In all, six trials were planted toEucalyptus grandisall having been felled in the last ten years. A large number of reports were published during this period based on this trial series particularly with respect to the development of models incorporating stand density as a function in growth models as well as standard taper, basal area and Site Index equations. The purpose of this report is not to re-evaluate published results but to provide a closure on this trial series, summarise the data graphically, provide a summary of growth models for the data over the entire period of growth and attempt to provide an explanation of the observed growth trends with a view to assisting foresters and managers formulate recommendations concerning stand density for a range of site productivities. In this respect the results of this trial series will be of value to a wide range of users, from the emerging growers and small-scale farmer who wish to maximize profit from his land in the shortest period of time, to the corporate growers where felling plans need to be more flexible. Increasing stems per hectare reduces the time to culmination of mean annual increment (MAI) and increases the magnitude of the MAI at the culmination. This effect was more pronounced on the higher productivity sites. For example, the time taken to culmination on the high productivity sites (SI5>22 m) was 4 to 5 years compared to 5 to 10 years on the medium productivity sites (SI516 to 22 m) and 12 to 13 years on the low productivity sites (SI5>16). The culmination of MAI usually coincided with the maximum difference in MAI between stand density treatments these differences becoming less in time particularly on high productivity sites. Therefore to capture the benefit of increased stems per hectare the stand should be harvested at culmination of the MAI. The current annual increments (CAIs) showed substantial variation from year to year caused by variable annual rainfall resulting in "false peaks" in the culmination of the MAI over time. The clonal material planted on trials on high productivity sites survived the drought periods much better than the seedlings but this was only translated into better volume growth at one site. On the low to medium productivity sites there were no great differences in survival or volume growth between the seedling and clonal material. Modelling of the size/density relationships for seedling and clonal material across all sites revealed that competition-induced mortality had only properly set in on the higher productivity sites later in the rotation, while two of the trials had been felled too early to reveal this and a third was on such a low productivity site that competition had yet to set in even after 14 years. Because of this, mid-rotation mortality must be assumed to be solely drought related. The data also showed that critical diameters for late-rotation competition-related mortality are smaller for seedling material compared to clonal material. The effects of drought on height growth resulted in widely varying estimation of dominant height at 5 years (SI5) throughout the rotation. This could result in considerable errors in growth estimation if Site Index models are being used retrospectively for prediction of volume.
