TI  - Upscaling new rice for Africa adoption in northern Uganda and south Sudan: socio-economic and technical prerequisites.
T2  - 11th African Crop Science Proceedings, Sowing innovations for sustainable food and nutrition security in Africa. Entebbe, Uganda, 14-17 October, 2013
M3  - Conference paper
AB  - New rice for Africa (NERICA) is widely seen as a major crop to improve food security and livelihoods in Africa. It is also suitable for the rain fed conditions of Northern Uganda and South Sudan which are post conflict areas having high demand for rice but associated with low supply of quality rice seed and grain. By intensifying rice production for lowland and upland areas, significant increase in rice production and productivity can be attained. Rice production in most areas is undertaken in the wetlands, while NERICA upland rice with relatively higher yields than the conventional African rice species has a shorter growth cycle of about 90- 115 days, enabling double cropping and minimising on drought damage as well as encroachment of wetlands. Therefore, ASARECA is funded a collaborative project involving CABI, NaCRRI, FICA, AAH-I and MAFCRD-RSS in Northern Uganda and South Sudan to upscale the adoption of NERICA in the two countries. A situation analysis was conducted to ascertain the socio-economic and technical imperatives for success of the endeavour in both Northern Uganda and South Sudan. The analysis involved 390 rice growers selected through multi-stage random sampling from Amuru and Gulu Districts in Uganda, and Morobo and Yei Counties in South Sudan. Data was collected using structured questionnaires, interviews, focus group discussions and documentary analysis. It was established that most of the farmers that is 55% in Northern Uganda and 50% in South Sudan had primary level of education. The level of education was relatively lower in South Sudan and among the women farmers in both countries. This means that participatory approaches would be best for up scaling NERICA production. There was limited use of good agronomic practices, training and access to the improved technologies especially seed and capacity to adopt the technologies. The area under rice production in both countries was significantly (p<0.05) lower than the total land area, meaning that there exists potential for increasing the area under rice production through technical support and creating awareness about the ability of rice production to increase food security and household incomes. The yield of rice was an average of 1.4 MT ha-1 which is relatively lower than the potential yield (4 MT ha-1) that could be achieved under good agronomic practices using the improved technologies. There are no efficiently functioning partnerships and innovation platforms to facilitate the production, processing and marketing of rice. Information on production, processing and marketing is limited due to poor packaging and dissemination efforts. The ASARECA project facilitated adoption of NERICA through the use of innovation platforms, provision of training services, linking various stakeholders, supply of improved seed through collaboration with reliable seed companies. The project has also improved the documentation and sharing of best practices, technologies, experiences and lessons learnt for up scaling NERICA production.
