AU  - Jayaramareddy, Jayaramareddy
AU  - Shivaraj, B.
TI  - An analysis of crop insurance utilization in Gadag District, Karnataka.
T2  - Mysore Journal of Agricultural Sciences
M3  - Journal article
AB  - Flood, drought, onslaught of pest and diseases and others are imminent agriculture production risks in India as about 40 million hectares of land is prone to floods and 68 per cent of agricultural land is vulnerable to drought. Among several risk mitigating strategies, crop insurance is a prominent one. But the crop insurance compensation is skewely distributed, because scheme is based on area approach. The performance of crop insurance in Karnataka is economically disappointing, due to mounting losses. The claim ratio and loss ratio were 4.23 and 0.13 respectively, for Karnataka and 1.47 and 0.027 for Gadag district in Karnataka. The Gadag district had performed better than the Karnataka in respect of crop insurance. About, 13 per cent of insured farmers in the district received benefits from crop insurance. The National Agricultural Insurence Scheme is more popular among farmers of Gadag district. Non-loanee farmers participated and benefited more from crop insurance than loanee farmers. The respondents in the district viewed that the scheme is still not so popular among the farm households. The compensation disbursed under the scheme was not even sufficient to cover 50 per cent of cost of cultivation. They prefer to pay a higher rate of premium for a reasonable and larger coverage of their cost of cultivation. Crop insurance scheme should be made mandatory for all farmers to avoid the problem of adverse selection and the moral hazards.
