TI  - Problems and gender involvements in rice production in selected flood prone lowland area of northeast Bangladesh.
T2  - Journal of Socioeconomic Research and Development
M3  - Journal article
AB  - This study was conducted to determine rice production problems and gender involvement in rice farming in the flood-prone lowland areas of northeast Bangladesh. Data were collected through participatory group discussion methods with different categories of participants in Habiganj district. Among the various rice production problems, lack of capital and scarcity of quality seeds were found to be the principal problems, followed by flash floods during harvesting of boro rice, insect infestation, shortage of irrigation facilities, rat infestation, lack of drying facilities during harvest time of boro rice, high price of agricultural inputs, lack of pest management knowledge, low price of rice at harvest, scarcity of agricultural labour during boro harvest, and the influence of money lenders or middlemen. Identified rice production problems by different levels of participants were highly similar. Women were found involved mainly in household-related activities of rice production while men engaged in field-oriented activities of rice cultivation.
