AU  - Lemons e Silva, C. F.
AU  - Barbosa Neto, J. F.
TI  - Combining ability of maize genotypes for flooding tolerance.
T2  - Ciencia Rural
M3  - Journal article
AB  - In southern Brazil, maize could be an alternative for cultivation in flooded areas. However, the development of genotypes tolerant to flooding is fundamental to make this option economically feasible. A greenhouse experiment was conducted to determine the general and specific combining ability and reciprocal effect for flooding tolerance in maize genotypes. The analysis was based on a diallel cross among 4 inbreds: 2 flooding tolerant (CT954280 and CT954330) and 2 sensitive inbreds (CT966200 and CT966208). Data were recorded for root dry matter, plant dry matter, plant height, root length, and leaf chlorophyll content. Genetic variability among the inbreds was detected. Both additive and non-additive effects were important in the determination of the inheritance of flooding tolerance in maize. The correct choice of the female parent is fundamental for tolerant hybrid production, since maternal effects were relevant. Among the analysed genotypes, CT954330 presented the highest general combining ability and may be indicated as a preferential progenitor in crosses that aim to increase flooding tolerance.
