TI  - Demonstration of a climate-resilient multitrophic pen system in Vembanad Lake, Kerala, India.
T2  - World Aquaculture
M3  - Journal article
AB  - This article discussed the ecological significance and current status of Vembanad Lake, the longest lake in India, is spread across an area of more than 2000 square kilometers. It was designated a Wetland of International Importance under the Ramsar Convention in 2002 and is also classified as a "Critically Vulnerable Coastal Area" as per CRZ Notification, 2011 by the Ministry of Environment, Forest and Climate Change. With this current situation of Vembanad lake the authors highlights adaptation strategies to cope with climate change by devising various income enhancement programs for clam fishers. The adaptation strategy recommended by CIFRI relative to climate change is diversification of livelihood systems, where farmers alternate between farming in Climate-Resilient Pen Structures (CRPS) and fishing in response to seasonal and interannual variation in shellfish availability was also presented.
