ED  - Dam, A. A. van
TI  - Community-based fish culture in seasonal floodplains.
T2  - Integrated irrigation and aquaculture in West Africa: concepts, practices and potential
M3  - Book chapter
M3  - Conference paper
AB  - During the rainy season in extensive river floodplains and deltaic lowlands, floods lasting several months render the land unavailable for crop production for several months each year. These waters are considerably underutilized in terms of managed aquatic productivity. This raises the opportunity to enclose parts of these floodwater areas to produce a crop of specifically stocked aquatic organisms aside from the naturally occurring "wild" species that are traditionally fished and are not affected by the culture activity, overall resulting in more high-quality, nutrient-dense food production and enhanced farm income for all stakeholders, notably the poor. The WorldFish Centre and its national partners recently tested the concurrent rice-fish culture in the shallower flooded areas and the alternating rice-fish culture in the deep-flooded areas of Bangladesh and Vietnam through a community-based management system. Results indicate that community-based fish culture in rice fields can increase fish production by about 600 kg/ha/year in shallow flooded areas and up to 1.5 tonnes/ha/year in deep-flooded areas, without reduction in rice yield and wild fish catch.
