AU  - Bedamatta, Rajshree
TI  - Employment of the rural labour force in India - the current trends and future prospects.
T2  - Indian Journal of Agricultural Economics
M3  - Journal article
AB  - This paper discusses the diverse and contradictory estimations on employment patterns in India. The Periodic Labour Force Survey (PLFS) and Centre for Monitoring Indian Economy's Consumer Pyramids Household Survey (CMIE) results indicate that job losses have intensified post-2016 and are continuing. The COVID 19 exogenous shock came at the most inopportune time when non-agriculture held opportunities for a discouraged workforce. The reverse migration of workers from towns and urban centers to villages due to draconian lockdowns will spell disaster for the rural areas as there is no work. Agriculture has stagnated to a point where it has no chance of revival without appropriate and significant public support programmes ranging from technology adoption, extension services, price support mechanisms, training programmes, and income subsidies. Female labour force participation needs immediate and urgent policy attention. The female labour force statistics need adequate attention beginning with the implementation of the ILO resolution of 2013 in Indian employment-unemployment statistics. There is a dire need to restore the National Sample Survey Organisation (NSSO) employment-unemployment rounds with improved methodologies.
