AU  - Soth, Jens
AU  - Witteveen, Annet
TI  - Igniting a spark for landscape restoration.
T2  - Rural 21
M3  - Journal article
AB  - A growing demand for land, water and other natural resources in combination with human-induced climate change has put increasing pressure on nature while rapidly eroding the basis for people's livelihoods. In order to counter this, development practitioners are increasingly setting their sights on a landscape approach. Helvetas Swiss Intercooperation has pinpointed four elements as relevant to successful landscape restoration processes: (1) combine action on communal land as well as on farmland; (2) integrate private sector actors and high agroecological ambition; (3) local spatial planning from the bottom; and (4) inclusion of women and youth. An example from Tanzania, the "Kijani Hai" landscape project, shows how the cornerstones mentioned are capable of kick-starting the transformation from a landscape threatened by soil erosion, deforestation, drought and diminishing quality of livelihoods to a regenerative, diverse and climate-resilient landscape with manifold income opportunities.
