AU  - Prasad, Narayan
TI  - Farmers' cognitive perspectives in dealing with climate risk: a narrative review.
T2  - Climate change, adaptation and gender: policy, practice and methodological underpinnings
M3  - Book chapter
AB  - Gender-responsive approaches are important to increase adoption (rate, behaviour and adaptive capacity) of climate-resilient strategies (CRS) to address climate change. Nonetheless, the psychological behaviour of individuals influences behavioural intention to adopt. This study uses new methodological approaches that go beyond gender being considered as biological and visible difference; for example, differences in terms of access and control over resources reduce individual capacity. The text includes theoretical and methodological approaches which consider individuals' behaviour and knowledge. The Protection Motivation Theory (PMT) approach is used to understand the cognitive behaviour of the farmer. Before adoption of CRS can take place, the farmer must accept and perceive the changes in, and components of, knowledge, experience and perception, which are a precursor to the adoption of CRS. Due to varying degrees of control as well as responsibilities, women and men have different adaptative capacities and other enabler (/barrier) factors which motivate (/discourage) them from the adoption (/dis-adoption) of any solutions.
